"CORE_NARRATIVE: Real-world light field depth estimation catastrophically fails in non-Lambertian regions because traditional methods rely on a global Lambertian assumption and view consistency, which are severely violated by specular and scattering materials. To overcome this, we propose a component-aware adaptive strategy that leverages physics-driven angle-frequency analysis to dynamically schedule specialized depth estimation branches based on continuous material weights. This approach fundamentally resolves view consistency failures in complex mixed scenes, enabling robust and physically interpretable 3D reconstruction for critical applications like autonomous driving.\n\nINTRO_HOOK: Open with a striking real-world failure case, such as an autonomous driving system misjudging the distance to a specular car hood due to \"texture copying\" artifacts caused by broken view consistency. This immediately grounds the abstract problem of non-Lambertian reflections in a critical, high-stakes practical application, highlighting the urgent need for robust depth estimation.\n\nGAP_BRIDGE: Highlight that while existing EPI-based and purely data-driven methods attempt to handle reflections, they implicitly force a global Lambertian prior or lack physical interpretability, leading to severe generalization drops on extreme mixed materials. This gap necessitates our transition to a physics-driven framework that explicitly decouples reflection types via Radiation Tensor Field (RTF) rank constraints and angle-spectrum mapping before estimating depth.\n\nMETHOD_JUSTIFY: Because the motivation demands abandoning the global Lambertian assumption, we design an MRI-inspired angle-frequency analysis and dual-mask physical model to accurately quantify pixel-level diffuse, specular, and scattering weights. These continuous material weights directly justify the dynamic scheduling and component-weighted fusion of distinct depth branches (e.g., EPI for diffuse, photometric stereo for specular), ensuring each pixel is processed by its physically optimal estimator.\n\nEXPERIMENT_VALIDATE: Design targeted ablation and comparative experiments on datasets rich in extreme non-Lambertian materials (e.g., metals, frosted glass) to quantitatively prove that our adaptive branch scheduling eliminates texture copying and significantly reduces depth errors in specular/scattering regions. Success will be validated by demonstrating superior robustness and physical consistency (e.g., BRDF weight errors <10%) compared to baseline methods that blindly enforce global view consistency.\n\nCONCLUSION_ECHO: Reiterate that by replacing the flawed global Lambertian assumption with a physics-based, component-aware adaptive scheduling mechanism, we have successfully neutralized the depth prediction failures caused by non-Lambertian materials. Conclude by emphasizing that this breakthrough restores the reliability of light field technologies, paving the way for their robust deployment in complex, real-world 3D perception tasks."